The Sydney Opera House is a multi-venue performing arts centre in Sydney. Located on the foreshore of Sydney Harbour, it is widely regarded as one of the world's most famous and distinctive buildings and a masterpiece of 20th-century architecture.

Designed by Danish architect Jorn Utzon, but completed by an Australian architectural team headed by Peter Hall, the building was formally opened by Queen Elizabeth II on 20 October 1973 after a gestation beginning with Utzon's 1957 selection as winner of an international design competition. The Government of New South Wales, led by the premier, Joseph Cahill, authorised work to begin in 1958 with Utzon directing construction. The government's decision to build Utzon's design is often overshadowed by circumstances that followed, including cost and scheduling overruns as well as the architect's ultimate resignation.

The building and its surrounds occupy the whole of Bennelong Point on Sydney Harbour, between Sydney Cove and Farm Cove, adjacent to the Sydney central business district and the Royal Botanic Gardens, and near to the Sydney Harbour Bridge.

input: What is DevSecOps?
output:
DevSecOps is a development and security approach that leverages DevOps practices, and combines them with the security practices of security development lifecycle (SDL). It consists of three main practices:

-   Security Development Life Cycle (SDL), which includes security requirements analysis, security design, security testing, and security release management.
-   Continuous integration (CI), which includes continuous integration and continuous testing.
-   Continuous delivery (CD), which includes continuous integration, continuous testing, and continuous delivery.

DevSecOps also includes a separation of responsibilities between security development and operations, and between development and security operations. DevSecOps is a more agile, flexible, and collaborative process than the traditional waterfall development and security operations lifecycle, which are more operationally heavyweight.
label: DevSecOps is an augmentation of DevOps with security integrated into the DevOps approach. It has been growing in recent years as producing secure software is becoming a top priority for companies.

input: What happens when the sun goes down?

But during the winter months, the sun doesn't set until later in the evening. This is because the Earth orbits the sun in a tilted position. When the Earth is tilted toward the sun, the sun stays above the horizon all day. But when the Earth is tilted away, the sun sets below the horizon during the day. This is how we experience longer days in the Northern Hemisphere.

input: Who is Marshall Strickland
output:
Marshall Strickland was an American football coach and athletic director. He was the eighth head football coach at The College of William & Mary in Williamsburg, Virginia and the seventh athletic director. Strickland began his career as an assistant at his alma mater, the College of William & Mary, in 1950. In 1955, he was promoted to offensive line coach and later assistant head coach. In 1964, he became the head coach at William & Mary after serving as the school's athletic director for three years. He held that position for the next 30 years, first as an assistant from 1965 to 1968 and then as head coach from 1969 to 1980. In 1984, he began a five-year tenure as athletic director before retiring in 1989.

After retiring from coaching, Strickland returned to his alma mater as the head of athletics. He was a member of the board of visitors of The College of William & Mary from 1995 to 1999. He spearheaded the renovation of the William & Mary football stadium in 2005, which was completed in time for the 2006 season. In March 2008, Strickland announced that he would step down in July, but remained on the school's board of visitors until November 2008. In December 2008, he announced that his daughter, Sheila, would succeed him as William & Mary's head coach. She was in her sixth year as head coach at the time of her father's retirement.

input: Who are the most influential female computer scientists of all time?
output: These days, it is hard to think of a computer scientist who is not female.  However, in the 1950s and 1960s, there were very few women in this field and the most influential ones were Grace Hopper, Alta M. Green, and Ada Lovelace.  Grace Hopper was perhaps the best known computer scientist of the time and is often referred to as the "mother of the modern computer" in recognition of her role in the invention of the computer.  She is also credited with coining the term "computer science" during the early 1950s.  Hopper's work at the United States Navy'sCode & Language School is where she first used a computer to solve a problem and broke the barrier for women to be involved in computer science.  Her legendary ability to solve complex problems with a computer quickly made her the go-to person for the Navy on computing matters.  Alta M. Green had a similar career trajectory and is also considered one of the first computer scientists.  The reason for this is that she not only used her background as a mathematician to understand the logic of the digital computer but also was able to teach herself programming when she needed to.  This made her an invaluable member of the MIT AI Lab and one of the most influential computer scientists of the time.  Her work with the AI Lab was extended when she wrote the first computer program to solve the famous traveling salesman problem in 1957.  This allowed computers to be used on more complex problems and provided an entry point for women to enter computer science.  Alta M. Green also did early work on the design of a compiler and also invented the first symbolic computer program known as the "Semantic Analyzer" which was used to help develop the first compiler.  This led to her being recognized by the National Academy of Sciences as "one of the most influential scientists of the 20th century".  She was also a pioneer for better representation of computer code on paper and created the first computer language that utilized markup symbols to write computer code.  These achievements were followed by Ada Lovelace, who is often referred to as the "mother of computer science".  Lovelace was one of the few women at the time who had a background in mathematics and knew how to program.  Her work was widely used in the development of the first computer algorithms and programs and is considered as the "mother of AI".  She is also credited with the first ever computer algorithm that utilized mathematics to model the behavior of objects
label:
Ada Lovelace
Grace Hopper
Hedy Lamarr
Annie Easley
Mary Wilkes
Adele Goldberg
Radia Perlman
Katherine Johnson

Droughts can also be triggered by a rapid drop in atmospheric pressure.  A drought can impact supplies if rainfall drops below normal levels.  Droughts can increase or decrease food supplies if they impact crops or pastures, respectively.  If a drought impacts food supplies, this can have a significant impact on local populations.
label: A drought can reduce the amount of crops that can be grown due to less water being available for the farms in an area. input: How can introverts maintain friendship.

Introverts are hard to befriend because their inner life is often more interesting and engaging than the social world in which they exist. You can do this by having conversations about your experiences, thoughts, feelings, and emotions. You can also discuss your inner life in the form of art, writing, or other creative expression.

3. Find common interests. Introverts often have their own unique interests and passions. However, introverts may not find the other introvert to share their interests. In this case, you can find common interests that you and the introvert in your life share. For example, you can find common interests by meeting for coffee or by joining the introvert for a hike.

4. Be honest and open. Introverts often have their own unique way of thinking and communicating. However, introverts often have the capacity to be more honest and open than extroverts. This means that introverts can be more honest about their own inner life and about their own struggles. For introverts, this can be quite freeing. It means that they don't have to worry about how they are perceived by the extrovert in their life.

- On the resource perspective, water, landscape and energy usage increased significantly and led to concerns on reduced natural habitats for birds and animals
- On the refuse management perspective, trashes, especially plastics, became a major concern both environmentally and economically. Hawaii passed state laws in 2019 and 2021 to ban using plastics in food service, beverage bottles, utensils, stirring sticks, polystyrene foam containers, and straws. These are the first state-wide bans on food service plastics in America. 
- On social effect perspective, there are tensions between Native Hawaiians and residents who hold negative views towards tourism and visitors and the increasingly booming tourism industry.

input: What are the ways to save money in gardening?
output: Saving money in gardening is a matter of choosing the right practices and tools.  Start by choosing the right type of soil.  Soil that is well-drained and somewhat fertile will allow plants to grow more vigorously and quickly than soil that is poorly drained or mostly clay soil.  Next, choose the right type of seeds.  The most common type of seeds is "annuals"  These are plants that come back every year.  Some plants that are good for gardeners to keep around for the long run include marigolds, nasturtiums, zinnias, onions, and snapdragons.  Annuals are easier to keep around than perennial plants, but they don't produce seeds, so they must be replanted after each growing season.  Other plants that are good for gardens but don't bring seeds are rhubarb, strawberries, and raspberries.  Plants that produce seeds include peas, beans, corn, squash, squashes, cucumbers, pumpkins, and melons.  Some plants that are good for gardens but not for seed production are begonias, zinnias, petunias, phlox, cosmos, and snapdragons.  Last, decide on the size of your garden and follow the directions on the plant or the directions on the seed packet.  It is best to plant your seeds in the spring or summer, when the soil is warm and not frozen.  After planting, water the seeds thoroughly.  They will grow only if they receive adequate water.  Once your garden is established start with annual plants and add perennial plants as they mature.  If you want to save money on plants and seeds, buy plants at a discount nursery or from online sources.  The plants will last for several years and will give you many opportunities to save money.
label:
1. Avoid buying potting mix by making your own potting soil
2. Compost your food scraps to make your own soil
3. Avoid buying seed germinating trays by using tofu trays and other recycled food trays to germinate seeds

5. Avoid buying plants from the store by germinating plants from seed yourself
6. Collect rainwater for your plants to avoid using municipal water
7. Re-use water from rinsing vegetables/rice to water your plants to minimize the use of municipal water

input: Why is cold water coming out of my water heater?
output:
Your water heater is likely leaking. Cold water is coming out of your water heater because cold water is coming out of your water heater. There are a couple things that may be causing the leak. First, the water heater could be leaking at the main water line, which is typically located outside of your home near the curb. In this case, you will likely see cold water outside of your home near the curb.

If the leak is coming from the water heater, then it's possible that the water tank is damaged and is leaking water. This is typically caused by overloading the valve or a damaged or cracked tank. If the leak is coming from the water tank, you can replace the tank or the gasket around the tank valve. If the leak is coming from the valve, you can replace the valve.
label:
If your gas water heater is not working, first check to see if:

 - Is the water heater leaking? If so, turn off the water and gas to the heater, and contact a plumber to replace the heater.
 - Do you smell gas around your heater? If so, you likely have a gas leak--turn off the gas line to the heater and contact a plumber to replace the heater.
 
If neither of these are issues, check to see if the pilot light for you heater is lit. This is likely hidden behind a panel or door on the bottom of the front of the heater.  If the pilot light is not lit, follow the instructions to try re-lighting it.

If the pilot light does not light or continues to go out after heating the water, the thermal coupling on the water heater likely needs to be replaced. Contact a plumber to have this replaced.

Generally speaking, traditional tank-based, gas water heaters have a lifetime of 10-15 years. If the age water heater is within this range, you may want to prepare for replacing the water heater soon.

input: History of Linux
output:
History of Linux
-	Linus Torvalds created Linux kernel in 1991.
-	Linux reached 1 million users in late 1994.
-	Linux reached 2 million users in 1995.
-	Linux reached 5 million users in 1998.
-	Linux reached 10 million users in 2003.
-	Linux reached 15 million users in 2011.
label:
Linux, computer operating system created in the early 1990s by Finnish software engineer Linus Torvalds and the Free Software Foundation (FSF).

While still a student at the University of Helsinki, Torvalds started developing Linux to create a system similar to MINIX, a UNIX operating system. In 1991 he released version 0.02; Version 1.0 of the Linux kernel, the core of the operating system, was released in 1994. About the same time, American software developer Richard Stallman and the FSF made efforts to create an open-source UNIX-like operating system called GNU. In contrast to Torvalds, Stallman and the FSF started by creating utilities for the operating system first. These utilities were then added to the Linux kernel to create a complete system called GNU/Linux, or, less precisely, just Linux.

input: Thinking about public opinion, what is the significance of “issue consistency” and “levels of conceptualization”?

Issue consistency is the consistency of a person’s beliefs or opinions on a specific issue. Public opinion is a social phenomenon that can be analyzed at different levels. At the most basic level, we can observe people’s opinions on a specific issue. In other words, we can observe the “level of conceptualization” of a person. The concept of issue consistency refers to how a certain issue or a particular belief is consistent or inconsistent for a person. For example, a person who believes in global warming is likely to be a “global warming supporter” or “pro-environmentalist”. In contrast, someone who is a “pro-business” or a “anti-environmentalist” is unlikely to believe in global warming.

Issue consistency is another level of analysis that refers to how a person’s opinions and beliefs on an issue are consistent or inconsistent. For example, issue consistency refers to whether someone believes in global warming or not, whether they are “pro-environmentalist” or “anti-environmentalist”. The concept of issue consistency is more complicated than that. It is also important to consider the “levels of conceptualization” of a person.

First, we can observe people’s preferences or attitudes on a certain issue. For example, it is common to see people’s “approval” on a specific party or a certain issue. “Approval” refers to how people feel about a particular issue. It is also possible to observe people’s “preference” on an issue. People who prefer a certain party or issue are called “supporters” or “supporters of the party or issue”.

In addition to “preference” and “approval”, it is also possible to observe people’s “conceptualization” of an issue. The “level of conceptualization” refers to how a person views an issue. For example, it is common to see people’s “pro-environmental” or “anti-global warming” “conceptualizations”.

In summary, the concept of issue consistency refers to how a person’s opinions and beliefs are consistent or inconsistent. The concept of issue consistency is more complicated than that. It is also important to consider the “levels of conceptualization” of a person.

input: What are your views on the "First Principles" by "Thomas E. Ricks"
output:
"First Principles" is a non-fiction book written by US Army officer, former CIA officer, and national security advisor to Vice President Dick Cheney, Thomas E. Ricks. The book is about the decisions made in the years leading up to the Iraq War and the dilemmas faced by the Bush Administration. It was published by Penguin Press on November 11, 2007.

"First Principles" is a critical analysis of the Bush Administration's decision-making process during the Iraq War. Ricks' main focus is on the period from 2004 to 2006, which is called the "Iraqi Surge". He covers the decisions made by top administration officials such as Condoleezza Rice, Donald Rumsfeld, Paul Bremer, and John Negroponte. He also describes the challenges faced by the Bush Administration, such as the insurgency and al-Qaeda in Iraq, the lack of democracy, and the sectarian violence.

Ricks argues that Bush Administration officials were trapped in an "illusion of control". They believed that they could control the Iraq conflict through military means, negotiations, and reconstruction. However, they were unable to control the situation because of the insurgency and the lack of political will to reform Iraq. He also criticizes the Bush Administration for not having a clear exit strategy from Iraq.

input: What is the difference between AWD and 4WD?
output: AWD stands for "All Wheel Drive" and refers to the ability of a vehicle to operate only on all 4 wheel-driven wheels. A vehicle with AWD is able to operate without an auxiliary "4WD" mode. It's the same as having 4WD in a car, but in a truck, it means the engine can be switched to "D" mode to help get the truck moving if the driver leaves the clutch in gear when the truck is parked.
label:
AWD is a system that without driver intervention, shifts power between the rear and front wheels. This system is typically found on light-duty SUVs or passenger cars. The AWD drive system is designed for mild inclement weather conditions such as light snow, ice and rain. It is not designed for off-roading or severe weather conditions such as heavy snow or mud. This is where the 4WD system comes into the picture. 

4WD is a system that includes a transfer case that directly applies power to the rear axle, both front and rear axles and in some cases, only to the front axle. In addition, some 4WD systems include lower gear ratio options, locking hubs and lockers in the axles that force an equal amount of power to each wheel. All this taken together enables a 4WD system to enable a vehicle to navigate through deep snow, mud, over rocks and other obstacles with ease. The 4WD system is most commonly found on trucks, Jeeps and other purpose-built vehicles designed for heavy-duty use, whether for work or pleasure.

input: What are some ways I can improve my general health during my work day?

input: Why are some people vegetarian?
output: Most people who are vegetarians choose to reduce or eliminate consumption of animal products such as meat, poultry, fish, and dairy.  The animal agriculture industry is the second largest industry in the United States.  It is estimated that more than 90 percent of all animals raised for food end up in a grocery store.  If all animals raised for food were to become vegetarians, the demand for animal products would need to increase by 300 percent!  If the demand for animal products increases by 300 percent, you can be sure that animal agriculture will find a way to increase production.  The best way to reduce your consumption of animal products is to go plant based.  A plant based diet is rich in vitamins, minerals, fiber, and antioxidants.  It is also much lower in saturated fat and cholesterol than a typical North American diet.  A plant based diet has been shown to help prevent and treat a number of chronic diseases and conditions including heart disease, diabetes, and cancer.  Not only does a plant based diet help you stay healthy, it also reduces the negative environmental impact of animal agriculture.  The livestock industry is the second largest source of climate changing greenhouse gas emissions.  A plant based diet can also help reduce the climate change impact of animal agriculture.  The average person who goes plant based and cuts their animal product consumption by 50 percent will save money, reduce the climate change impact of animal agriculture, and help prevent and treat a number of chronic diseases and conditions.
label: There are many reasons for being vegetarian. Some religions prohibit eating meat. Other people prefer not eat meat because they consider it immoral. The environmental impact of the meat industry has convinced other groups of people to stop eating meat to reduce their carbon footprint. Lastly, some people simply do not enjoy the taste of meat, or find it too expensive to purchase.

input: What batting traits make a good baseball or softball hitter?
output: Batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage, or some other measure of batting performance are typically calculated by counting a batter's number of bases plus any bases that are scored but not accounted for in the batting metric.  That is, if the batter only goes 0-1 on a base when the batter "walks" into the base, then the batter only goes to first base and the batting metric can account for the batter going no further than first base.  Batting average, for example, is calculated by dividing the number of bases by the number of times a batter goes at least one base into the bag.
label:
There are many traits that great baseball and softball batters share.  Some of the most important are extreme confidence, sound batting mechanics, and coordination developed though a combination of talent and practice.  

All great hitters share some consistencies in their batting mechanics such as their lower half mechanics, their hand and bat path, and their head and eye movement.

With their lower half mechanics they generate powerful torque from the ground up by timing the planting their feet in a balanced position and forcefully rotating and opening their hips.  Hitting powerful line drives relies heavily on the barrel of the bat meeting the ball flush.  Batters increase the odds of this by keeping their hands in, connected to the back shoulder, and having one palm facing up and one palm facing down for as long as possible as the bat path travels through the strike zone.  Finally, all great hitters maintain consistent head and eye position throughout the motion. 

There are many nuances of batting mechanics that all great hitters share but these are some of the most important.

input: What kind of language is Shauraseni Prakrit
output: Shauraseni is a late Prakrit dialect of the Hindi-Punjabi language language family. It is spoken in the state of Rajasthan in India. The language was distinctly different from the Marwari-Punjabi variety used in the rest of the state.
label:
Shauraseni Prakrit was a Middle Indo-Aryan language and a Dramatic Prakrit. Shauraseni was the chief language used in drama in medieval northern India. Most of the material in this language originates from the 3rd to 10th centuries, though it was probably a spoken vernacular around the 2nd century BCE in the ancient state of Surasena. 

Among the Prakrits, Shauraseni is said to be the one most closely related to Classical Sanskrit in that it is derived from the Old Indian Indo-Aryan dialect of the Madhyadesa on which Classical Sanskrit was mainly based. Its descendants include the languages of the Hindi Belt, the Central Zone of modern Indo-Aryan or Hindi languages, the standard registers of the Hindustani language based on the Delhi dialect.

Rafael Nadal's ability on clay is mostly due to the surface itself. This may appear to be a quip, but the particular qualities of claycourts - which distinguish them from grass and hardcourts - are a fundamental reason why Rafael Nadal has dominated the surface the way he has.

What distinguishes clay? It's sluggish and bouncy. Fundamentally, clay reduces the speed of the ball once it bounces on the surface. Of course, there's more to it than just making the game slow and monotonous, but that's the distinguishing quality of a claycourt.

The surface is also less skiddish than grass or hard, allowing the ball to bounce high, which suits Rafael Nadal's high topspin-based game.

input: how to fight a speeding ticket?
output:
There are several possible avenues to pursue when facing a speeding ticket.  First and foremost, you should consult with an experienced attorney.  Your lawyer should examine the circumstances surrounding your ticket, assess your chances of winning the case and help you to choose the most effective course of action.  

Another approach is to engage an aggressive defense attorney.  An aggressive defense attorney is one that will fight on your behalf and will likely try to negotiate a settlement with the prosecutor to reduce or dismiss the charges against you.  An aggressive defense attorney will likely spend more time going over discovery documents with you, gaining a better understanding of the case and the evidence against you.  He or she will also be better able to communicate with you and help you to understand the likely outcomes of your case.  

A third approach is to simply pay the ticket, either up front or in installments.  While this may not seem like the most attractive strategy, it is not uncommon for a defendant to pay a speeding ticket in full or in part.  There are two main reasons that a defendant may be inclined to pay a speeding ticket.  First, a defendant's insurance may cover the speeding ticket.  Second, a defendant may simply not want to incur the time and expense of a trial if they believe they will lose.  

On the other hand, paying a speeding ticket may not be the best strategy either.  If you are caught speeding by the police and your insurance carrier doesn't pay the ticket, your insurance carrier may take action against you (e.g., deny you coverage, restrict access to your car) and place a lien on your car.  

If you are not insured, paying the ticket will likely result in a larger judgment being entered against you in the event that you are convicted.  The judgment will likely fall on your car title and your car will be impounded.  As a result you may have to spend more money in order to redeem your car.  

A final approach is to settle the case without going to trial.  In such a case, the prosecutor will likely offer to dismiss the speeding ticket in exchange for a payment from the defendant.  If you are willing to make a payment towards the ticket, you may be able to avoid going to trial entirely or at least significantly reduce the charge against you.  

An experienced attorney can help you select the most appropriate course of action.
label: Three common ways to resolve a speeding tickets are 1. taking a defensive driving course: it takes about 20 hours to complete the course content but you can speed it up by playing the videos at 2x speed with a chrome plug-in. Some people just let the video play like background noise and do whatever is on the side.  2. hire an attorney to take care of it, the cost depends on your ticket details and varies based on attorneys. But it is the most care-free way as the attorney deals with the court on your behalf. There is no guarantee it always succeeds though. 3. go to the court yourself and fight it. This takes a lot of gut because you will need to face the judge and prosecuting attorney or the traffic policy on the court the defend yourself.

Sport routes are routes that are new to the climber.  The routes are rated from 5.9 to 5.12.  5.10 is typically not rated, and 5.11 and 5.12 can be rated up to V14 and harder.  

Bouldering is a great way to stay fit and stay in shape.  The climbing gyms offer a variety of exercises and sports to keep you engaged.  Often, someone will ask you what sport you want to try next.  If you have always wanted to try Lacrosse, that is a sport that someone will recommend!  Bouldering is a great sport for all ages and both genders.  Bouldering will challenge you physically, while at the same time it will challenge your mental strength and grit.

input: Why do human beings react slow on climate changes?

Human beings didn't evolve to live in a climate of instant change. In fact, our species has survived many climate changes in the past. But these past climate changes weren't gradual. They were massive, sudden shifts that were violent, sudden, and often dangerous.  

Today's climate changes are part of a trend of more gradual climate changes. The opposite is true of our ancestors' climates. Our bodies are built to respond to sudden changes. As a result, we can't fully adapt to today's climate changes without some additional time to prepare.

input: How do you wheelie a motorcycle?
output: A motorcyclist can wheelie their bike by first putting it into Drive, which turns the rear wheel.  They then depress the clutch until the bike is moving forward at a speed greater than the tension on the rear brake.  They then release the clutch, which allows the rider to re-engage the rear brake.  Next, the rider will perform a wheelie by lifting the bike up off the ground.  They will do this by engaging the clutch, allowing the bike to continue moving forward, and by releasing the clutch and re-engaging the rear brake.

input: what is the difference between ARM and x86 chipsets?

The primary difference is that x86 instructions are based on 32-bit logical addresses whereas ARM instructions are based on 16-bit physical addresses.
label: ARM uses Reduced Instruction Set Computing Architecture (RISC) whereas x86 uses Complex Instruction Set Computing Architecture (CISC). This allows softwares to be optimized for performance against ARM chipset as opposed to an 86 hardware approach to optimize. It would also be interesting to mention that ARM uses higher memory and less registers compared to x86.

input: How are odds different from probability?

In statistics, probability measures the number of outcomes in which a particular event occurred divided by the total number of possible outcomes. For example, the probability of rain on a given day would be based on, historically with similar conditions, the number of rainy days divided by a total number of days. The odds are measured as the number of events divided by the number of non-events. To contrast, probability would be the number of events divided by the sum of events and non-events.

input: How to do forecasting with small dataset?
output:
There are several options to do forecasting with small dataset:
1). Use online methods, like feed-forward neural networks and random forests
2). Use alternative data structures, like simple arrays
label:
Forecasting with small datasets can be challenging, as many traditional methods require larger amounts of data for accurate predictions.
Here are few approaches that can help you.

Simple moving average: This involves taking the average of a certain number of past data points, and using it as the forecast for the next period. This method can be effective for stable time series with no trend or seasonality.

Exponential smoothing: This method assigns exponentially decreasing weights to past observations, with more recent observations being given more weight. This method can be effective for time series with trend and/or seasonality.

ARIMA: The AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average (ARIMA) model is a popular choice for time series forecasting. It can be effective for small datasets if the underlying data follows a pattern that can be modeled using an ARIMA model.

input: What are the applications of game theory in NBA basketball?
output: In basketball, there are several strategies that the players can pursue to maximize their individual pay.  In particular, the strategies for the players on either side of the ball are very different.  The offense must find the best combination of shots to score while trying to minimize turnovers.  The defense must minimize the number of shots they let in while also minimizing the number of turnovers.  Therefore, it is of interest to understand how strategies can be designed that maximize the team's total score while minimizing the individual pay of the players.  The Nash Equilibrium is the best strategy for this situation.
label: Game theory studies the strategic interaction of rationale agents. The National Basketball Association (NBA) is the world's premier basketball league, which includes 30 teams across the United States and Canada. An example of game theory in the NBA is the "modern NBA", in which teams play stretch 4s (Power Forwards) and 5s (Centers) who can dribble, pass and shoot rather than simply rebound and dunk. This becomes the "strictly dominate" strategy as this allows the "modern" NBA team to shoot a higher volume of 3 pointers, which has a higher expected value per shot (40 Field Goal % times 3 = 1.2) than 2 pointers (50 Field Goal % times 2 = 1). The Golden State Warriors championship run in the 2010s with Kevin Durant and Draymond Green is a great example of this coaching and player construction strategy. Now nearly all NBA teams employ this strategy, so it is less effective (A Nash (Not Steve Nash!) Equilibrium).

input: Why is Africa the least wealthy continent per capita?
output: Historically, Africa was the poorest continent until World War II. Africa's colonial system was established in the 19th century, and as a result, Africa was dependent on Europe for its transportation routes, natural resources, and technology. At the beginning of the 20th century, Europe was the largest market for Africa's exports. However, as a result of World War I, Europe rapidly developed its industrial sector, whose subsequent growth led to an increased demand for Africa's exports. By the end of World War II, Africa had transformed from a colonial economy to a global economy. However, this growth came with a price, as Africa's growth rate rapidly declined after 1990. As a result, many African countries experienced economic stagnation, leading to high levels of poverty.
label: Africa is the least wealthy continent per capita due to a variety of factors including: geography, climate, tribalism, colonialism, the Cold War, neocolonialism, lack of democracy, and corruption.

input: Using examples taken from the text give me a rundown of the primary environments found in Yellowstone National Park.

The geothermal environment is found in the Yellowstone Caldera, which sits at the base of the park. The Yellowstone Caldera is the result of a massive volcanic explosion that occurred over 150 million years ago. The area is filled with hot water in the ground, and when the ground cools, the hot water is released as steam. The steam rises to the surface and creates a large caldera. You can see the steam rising from the ground at Yellowstone National Park. The world-class scenic environment is found near the geothermal area in the St. Joe Valley. St. Joe Valley is a scenic area with beautiful lakes and mountains. This area is also home to hundreds of wildlife species and over 400 species of plant life. The wild and scenic environment is found in the Snake Valley Unit, which is found on the eastern side of the park. Snake Valley Unit is a remote area that is home to thousands of wildlife species, but is also a popular destination for visitors.

Forests and grasslands dominate some areas of the park, while others offer the completely different experience of mountain ranges, lakes, and rolling prairies.  Some of the park's most unique features are the geysers and hydrothermal features.  In fact, Yellowstone is home to over half of the world's features like these. input: Can you give me some background on Perez v. Campbell
output: Cara Perez and Anthony Campbell were both charged with making false statements to the FBI. Perez lied to the FBI about her relationship with a confidential government informant and Campbell lied about the amount of money he was paid to recruit people to the United States to take part in a sham trial for criminals under the table. They were charged because they went to the law office of their former college professor, Stephen Gillers, to discuss their case. Gillers had been hired by the FBI to help them with their investigation into the case. Gillers had previously represented Perez in federal court. Gillers is a pro-bono attorney and he felt that he owed it to his former student to represent her even though he knew that she was facing prison time. Anthony Campbell was arrested the day before the trial was scheduled to begin. He had been providing Gillers with fake documents proving that he had paid the informant large sums of money to act as a government informant. The judge suspended the trial because of the false statements and it never took place. Anthony Campbell was convicted of making false statements and sentenced to probation. He also had to pay the informant $750,000 in restitution.
label:
Perez v. Campbell, 402 U.S. 637 (1971), was a case in which the Supreme Court of the United States held that Arizona's law suspending a driver's license was unconstitutional due to its conflict with the federal Bankruptcy Act under the Supremacy Clause of the Constitution.

The plaintiffs, Mr. Adolfo and Mrs. Emma Perez, were licensed uninsured motorists in the state of Arizona. Insurance was not required under Arizona law. Mr. Perez was involved in a traffic accident and, unable to pay the associated costs, soon filed for bankruptcy. Arizona, under its financial responsibility laws, withdrew the Perez' licenses, and the couple filed suit in district court, where their claim was denied. The Perez family's appeal to the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit was denied, and they subsequently appealed to the United States Supreme Court, which granted certiorari.

input: What is an optimisation problem?
output: For example, in the problem of designing a circuit to minimise the energy consumption, the objective function is the net energy consumption.
label:
In mathematics and computer science, an optimisation problem is typically a search problem in which the best solution is to locate among all feasible solutions. An optimisation problem can be categorised as continuous or discrete depending on the type of their variables. In a discrete optimisation problem, variables are discrete and countable. In contrast, continuous variables include infinitely uncountable values, for example, a variable over a non-empty range of real numbers. 

According to the number of objective functions, an optimisation problem is classified as single or multi-objective. A single-objective optimisation problem only involves one objective function to optimise. On the other hand, a multi-objective one considers two or more objectives simultaneously, which means the interaction between objectives has to be considered.

You can use a few plants to keep the bugs away: Marigold, Basil, Chives, Cilantro, Dill, Lemon Balm, and Thyme.

- Dig up the soil and add a handful of the dirt to a paper plate.
- Cover the plate and let sit for 24 hours.
- Once the soil has become moist, take the plate out and break it up into smaller pieces.
- Add the pieces in the soil.
- Water regularly.

input: Summarize the main components of a Kubernetes cluster control plane from this paragraph
output:
Kubernetes cluster control plane consists of 3 components:
Kubelet - The control plane component of the cluster, manages the underlying Kubernetes API server and its resources.
Controller - The control plane component is responsible for coordinating the work of the kubelet and enforcing policies on the cluster.
DaemonSet - A DaemonSet is a special type of StatefulSet that can be managed by a Kubernetes Controller.
label:
The kubernetes cluster control plane runs on one more more master nodes. The components are:
1. etcd - a key value datastore containing the configuration data of the cluster.
2. The api-server is a server which serves and updates the state of the kubernetes cluster. It watches etcd and keeps the clusters actual state in sync with its desired state.
3. The scheduler is a component which selects on which node an unscheduled pod should run, based on what each pod needs and what the nodes in the cluster can support.
4. The controller manager manages several controllers which keep the cluster in sync with its desired state.

input: How do you make an iced matcha latter?

Finally, add steamed milk or milk-based dairy-free milk such as rice milk or coconut milk for a richer taste. Lastly, stir the matcha and milk mixture.

input: Can you write a brief summary for the book "Braving the Wilderness" by Brene Brown?
output: Brene Brown is a best-selling author and one of the foremost experts on courage. She developed the concept of “bravery quotient” and has conducted research on courage in a variety of contexts. Bravery is a key leadership quality because it requires the courage to make difficult decisions and to take action. Brown argues that our definition of courage is too narrow and that we underestimate the importance of bravery in our lives. She argues that bravery is an innate quality that can be developed through practice. Brown describes the three components of courage: facing fear, taking action, and feeling the fear. She suggests that we practice courage by facing fear, taking action, and not reacting to fear. Brown gives many examples from her life of people she considers courageous.
label: Braving the Wilderness is a book about belonging, identity, and leadership. A core idea is that if you are courageous enough to stand alone in the name of the virtues and values you believe in, you can actually create more belonging for others. To brave the wilderness is not to go into the woods armored and ready to fight, but with an open heart and conviction steadying your spine.

input: Given this paragraph on French Revolution, what were the main causes
output: The French Revolution was a period of revolution and political instability in Europe that lasted from 1789 until 1799. It began in 1789 with the outbreak of the French Revolution, a series of political upheavals that eventually led to the establishment of a constitutional monarchy in France. The revolution spread rapidly throughout Europe, with revolutionary regimes established in Italy, the Netherlands, Belgium, Germany, and the United Kingdom, as well as among a number of German princely states. The revolution was overshadowed by the Napoleonic Wars, which began in 1807. The collapse of the French monarchy in 1815 heralded the end of the era of the European revolutions, which had lasted for more than a century.
label: The causes were multiple, including social, politic, and economic factors.

Singing a cappella is a common way to engage the audience and is a great way to showcase your talents.

In some cases, the company holding the auditions may also allow you to play recorded accompaniment at the audition. input: Is the recording of a person's last words reliable?
output: It is difficult to validate whether a person actually said those words, but it is not impossible.  It may be possible to confirm the person was in distress or in possession of thoughts and memories at the time; however, it would be hard to confirm whether those thoughts were the last thoughts of that person.  Given that it is difficult to determine if a person said their final thoughts, it is not surprising that many people feel that it is not reliable to record a person's last thoughts.  However, it is still possible to record a person's last thoughts, and the recordings are often available to their families, friends, or caregivers.
label: Sometimes it is, while other times it may contain errors or deliberately misquoted.
